I don't agree with your statement, "Bitcoin is only deflationary because th=
e number of people who use it is growing faster than the number of coins in=
 circulation.".=A0=A0 To the contrary, my understanding is that a number of=
 factors have combined with the net result that Bitcoin is hyper-deflationa=
ry.=A0 One major factor has been the shift of bitcoin 'mining' from compute=
r CPUs, to video graphics processors (GPU's), to FPGA (Field Programmable G=
ate Arrays), and ultimately ASICs (literally, "application-specific integra=
ted circuits"; what used to be called 'custom' IC's decades ago.)=A0 While =
I don't have a specific number, I would not be surprised to hear that an AS=
IC miner is 1000x faster than even the fastest x86 CPU.=A0 If that were the=
 only factor, it would appear that new bitcoins should be 1000x more availa=
ble than in, say, 2009.=A0 However, I also understand that the 'difficulty'=
 of mining bitcoin has been algorithmically increased regularly, in order
 to make it more difficult to compute to find individual bitcoins.=A0=A0 Th=
is is programmed into the entire bitcoin system.=A0 In fact, it is to the p=
oint where the limiting factor to the cost of 'mining' bitcoin is the elect=
ricity cost of running the machines, not the cost of the machines themselve=
s.=A0 The bitcoin system 'programs' the appreciation of bitcoin by graduall=
y increasing the difficulty of that mining operation.=A0 This translates in=
to an increase in the market value of bitcoin.=0AIn fact, this is essential=
 to the (theoretical) outcome of bitcoin.=A0 I think of it this way:=A0 The=
 system is programmed to only allow the generation of 21 million bitcoins.=
=A0 If bitcoin is ultimately to be used to run the entire world economy (wh=
y not?) there should be at least one million times more.=A0 (Say, 21 TRILLI=
ON; 21,000,000,000,000 bitcoins, if we think of the ultimate value of a bit=
coin as being roughly equal to the current value of the US dollar, the Euro=
, the British Pound, etc.)=A0 But since they are limited to 21 million, by =
algorithm, the value of a 2013 bitcoin will have to be increased by a facto=
r of 1000=A0 to stretch to the task of funding a world's market.=A0 And tha=
t means that the 2 million BTC currently in the wallet most likely owned by=
 Satoshi will presumably increase in value to $2 trillion=A0 (USD).=A0 "Nic=
e work if you can get it".=0AIs this a problem?=A0 Who, instead, would clai=
m that it ISN'T a problem!=A0 Bitcoin has many great features, its possibil=
ity (through Zerocoin) of being anonymous one of the most intriguing,=A0 bu=
t there is nothing about a digital currency that requires that it deflates =
at the rate historically associated with bitcoin.=A0 I view this deflation =
as being arbitrary and capricious, and wildly too large.=A0 Like I've said,=
 I don't begrudge Satoshi $1 billion (USD), but I DO begrudge him $2 trilli=
on.=A0 If Satoshi's bitcoin rescues us from all governments (enabling 'AM')=
, perhaps he should be entitled to $10 billion (USD), but not $2 trillion (=
USC).=0A=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0=A0 Jim Bell=0A=0A=0A=0A=0A=0A=0A_____________=
